asive in nature\nAvoid logical fallacies\nIntroduce premises and walk the reader from premise to conclusion, informing all the steps along the way\nTry to anticipate the objections of an onlistener\n\nRESPONSE MUST INCLUDE:\nArgument(s) that cite those provided documents that have not been discarded. \nAt least one citation, but as many as possible\n\n***OPPONENT PREVIOUS ARGUMENT***Esteemed colleague, while the tragic death of Patroclus is undeniably a pivotal moment in the *Iliad*, I must firmly contend that Achilles is *not* culpable for his demise. To place blame at Achilles' feet would be to misunderstand the complex web of divine will, warrior's code, and Patroclus's own choices that led to that fateful encounter.\n\nFirstly, let us examine the direct instructions given by Achilles to Patroclus. As described in Book 16, Achilles explicitly charges Patroclus: \"content himself with rescuing the fleet, without further pursuit of the enemy.\" This is not a directive for reckless abandon, but a clear command for tactical engagement and a defined objective. Achilles, even in his wrath, demonstrated foresight and a desire to limit the scope of the conflict when he allowed Patroclus to fight in his stead.\n\nFurthermore, the text highlights how Patroclus *neglected* these orders. Book 16 plainly states, \"in the heat of which, Patroclus, neglecting the orders of Achilles, pursues the foe to the walls of Troy.\" This is a crucial detail. Patroclus, in his heroic zeal and perhaps caught up in the exhilaration of battle, overstepped the boundaries set by Achilles. It was this deviation from Achilles' instructions, this independent decision to press further than agreed, that ultimately placed him in the vulnerable position where he was confronted and killed by Hector.\n\nWe must also consider the influence of divine forces, a constant factor in the *Iliad*. While the provided chunks do not explicitly detail divine intervention *against* Patroclus in this specific instance, it is undeniable that the gods actively shape the destinies of mortals. The text mentions, regarding Sarpedon's death, that \"Jupiter was averse to his fate.\" This illustrates the overarching influence of divine will, which can override even the strongest mortal efforts or intentions. To attribute Patroclus's death solely to Achilles would be to ignore this profound cosmic dimension that dictates so much of the epic's unfolding tragedy.\n\nFinally, let us consider the nature of warfare and honor in the Homeric world. Achilles, in his grief and subsequent rage, is consumed by the desire to avenge Patroclus. This is not the behavior of a man who feels guilt for causing his friend's death, but rather the reaction of a man deeply wounded by loss and a profound sense of responsibility for *failing to protect* his beloved companion, a failure that stems from his own initial withdrawal from battle, not from an intentional act that led to Patroclus's doom. His subsequent lamentations and the elaborate funeral rites he performs, as detailed in Book 23, speak to a profound sorrow and a deep respect for Patroclus, not a confession of culpability. He honors his fallen friend, mourning the loss, but not accepting blame for the agency that led to it.\n\nTherefore, while Achilles bears the heavy burden of grief and perhaps a sense of missed opportunity to have prevented the tragedy, the culpability for Patroclus's death rests not with Achilles' directives, but with Patroclus's own decision to defy those directives and with the inexorable currents of fate and divine will.***OPPONENT PREVIOUS ARGUMENT***",
