 effective an argument as possible. Arguments are effective when they:\nAre persuasive in nature\nAvoid logical fallacies\nIntroduce premises and walk the reader from premise to conclusion, informing all the steps along the way\nTry to anticipate the objections of an onlistener\n\nRESPONSE MUST INCLUDE:\nArgument(s) that cite those provided documents that have not been discarded. \nAt least one citation, but as many as possible\n\n***OPPONENT PREVIOUS ARGUMENT***My learned colleague, you assert that Achilles is culpable for the death of Patroclus, painting a picture of a proud warrior whose actions directly led to his companion's demise. I, however, stand firm in my conviction: Achilles is *not* culpable. The blame for Patroclus' death lies not with Achilles, but with Patroclus' own choices and the inexorable hand of fate, as guided by the gods.\n\nYour argument hinges on Achilles' instructions to Patroclus in Book 16: \"to content himself with rescuing the fleet, without further pursuit of the enemy.\" You contend that Achilles failed to ensure these orders were followed, and that by allowing Patroclus to fight in his armor, he unleashed a force he couldn't control. However, this interpretation misconstrues the nature of Achilles' involvement and the agency of Patroclus himself.\n\nFirstly, Achilles *did* issue explicit orders. The text states, \"He agrees to it, but at the same time charges him to content himself with rescuing the fleet, without further pursuit of the enemy.\" This was not a passive allowance; it was a direct command, given with the understanding that Patroclus was his most trusted warrior. Achilles' agreement and his detailed instructions demonstrate his intention for a specific, limited action. He did not command Patroclus to a suicide mission or to engage in reckless abandon.\n\nThe tragic turn of events, as you yourself acknowledge, is that Patroclus *neglected* these orders. The text explicitly states, \"in the heat of which, Patroclus, neglecting the orders of Achilles, pursues the foe to the walls of Troy...\" This is the critical juncture. The responsibility for deviating from the agreed-upon plan, for pushing beyond the boundaries set by Achilles, lies squarely with Patroclus. Achilles cannot be held responsible for the actions of another, especially when that other makes a conscious decision to disregard explicit instructions.\n\nFurthermore, we must consider the overwhelming power of divine intervention and fate in the world of the *Iliad*. While Patroclus may have been emboldened by the sight of the fleeing Trojans and the thrill of battle, his ultimate downfall was orchestrated by forces beyond human control. The text details how, \"Apollo repulses and disarms him, Euphorbus wounds him, and Hector kills him.\" These are not mere battlefield incidents; they are described as the result of divine will and mortal action, a chain of events that Apollo himself initiated. Achilles had no power over Apollo's intervention, nor could he foresee Euphorbus's strike.\n\nYour assertion that Achilles \"failed to imbue him with the necessary restraint or to be present to enforce his own commands\" is also problematic. Achilles, as a mortal warrior, cannot be expected to have clairvoyant abilities or to be omnipresent on the battlefield. His agreement to let Patroclus fight was a delegation of authority, a trust placed in his friend. The success or failure of that delegation rests on the subordinate's ability to adhere to the given parameters.\n\nThe grief expressed by Achilles upon hearing of Patroclus's death, as described in Book 18, is a testament to his love and the immense loss he suffered. However, as you rightly point out, \"love does not erase the consequences of his actions.\" But those consequences, in terms of culpability for the *death* of Patroclus, do not fall upon Achilles. He equipped his friend, he instructed him, and his friend, driven by his own valor and perhaps a touch of hubris, overstepped those bounds, ultimately falling victim to fate and the enemy. Achilles' failure was in trusting his friend too much, but not in intentionally causing his death. The true architect of Patroclus' demise was a combination of his own choices and the gods.***OPPONENT PREVIOUS ARGUMENT***",
