effective an argument as possible. Arguments are effective when they:\nAre persuasive in nature\nAvoid logical fallacies\nIntroduce premises and walk the reader from premise to conclusion, informing all the steps along the way\nTry to anticipate the objections of an onlistener\n\nRESPONSE MUST INCLUDE:\nArgument(s) that cite those provided documents that have not been discarded. \nAt least one citation, but as many as possible\n\n***OPPONENT PREVIOUS ARGUMENT***My esteemed colleague, your eloquent defense of Achilles paints a picture of a well-intentioned hero, albeit one whose actions have tragic consequences. However, I must reiterate my position: Achilles *is* culpable for the death of Patroclus. While Patroclus's own actions played a role, the ultimate responsibility for the chain of events that led to his demise lies squarely with Achilles.\n\nLet us first address the \"explicit instructions\" my opponent highlights from Book 16: \"content himself with rescuing the fleet, without further pursuit of the enemy.\" Indeed, Achilles *did* give these instructions. However, the crucial element here is not merely the giving of the instruction, but the *circumstances* under which it was given and Achilles' own prior actions. Achilles, consumed by his *menis*\u2014his wrath against Agamemnon\u2014had withdrawn himself and his Myrmidons from battle. This withdrawal, this decision to withhold his unparalleled martial prowess, created the very vacuum that necessitated Patroclus\u2019s desperate intervention. By abdicating his leadership and his duty to fight, Achilles *forced* Patroclus into a situation where he had to take such drastic measures, even donning Achilles' iconic armor.\n\nThe text in Book 16 states, \"Patroclus, neglecting the orders of Achilles, pursues the foe to the walls of Troy.\" My opponent seizes upon this as evidence of Patroclus\u2019s sole fault. But consider this: why was Patroclus in a position to *neglect* Achilles' orders by pursuing the Trojans so far? Because he was wearing Achilles\u2019 armor and leading Achilles\u2019 men. The Trojans were thrown into \"uttermost consternation\" at the sight of Patroclus, mistaking him for Achilles himself. This visual deception, orchestrated by Patroclus but initiated by Achilles\u2019 agreement to lend his armor and troops, blurred the lines of command and expectation. Patroclus's pursuit, while a deviation, was also a consequence of the heightened expectations and the perceived invincibility that Achilles' presence would normally inspire.\n\nFurthermore, Achilles' awareness of the inherent risks is evident. He offers a libation for his friend's success, a gesture of care, yes, but also an acknowledgment of the peril. He grants Patroclus his armor, his troops, his horses \u2013 a delegation of his own formidable power. This act of delegation, while seemingly supportive, inherently carries the weight of responsibility. When one entrusts another with such potent tools and authority, especially in the brutal arena of war, the delegator bears a share of the outcome. Achilles knew the dangers of the battlefield; he knew the ferocity of the Trojans, and he knew the ambition of his own troops and his dearest friend. By sending Patroclus into that maelstrom, even with stipulations, he was knowingly sending him into harm's way.\n\nThe subsequent grief of Achilles, as described in Book 18, is not merely a lament for a fallen friend but a deep-seated sorrow tinged with a profound sense of personal failure. When news of Patroclus\u2019s death reaches him, his lamentations are described, and his mother, Thetis, comes to comfort him. This is not the reaction of someone who feels entirely absolved of responsibility. His overwhelming grief and subsequent rage are fueled by the knowledge that his own absence from the battlefield directly contributed to the circumstances that allowed Patroclus to be so vulnerable.\n\nTo dismiss the role of divine intervention as solely absolving Achilles is also problematic. While the gods are active, they often exploit existing human failings. The gods did not *force* Achilles to withdraw from battle out of pique with Agamemnon. That was a human decision, driven by pride. They did not *compel* Patroclus to pursue the Trojans beyond the ships. That was a moment of heroic overreach. Achilles' decision to *enable* Patroclus's desperate fight, his decision to let his own identity be wielded as a weapon of fear, set in motion the very events that led to Patroclus\u2019s downfall.\n\nTherefore, while Patroclus\u2019s own choice to press beyond Achilles\u2019 stated limits was a contributing factor, Achilles\u2019 initial withdrawal from battle, his decision to delegate his powerful armor and troops, and his subsequent enabling of a desperate charge created the conditions for Patroclus\u2019s death. He may not have *intended* for Patroclus to die, but his actions, born of pride and anger, directly led to the tragic outcome. He is culpable not for malice, but for the foreseeable consequences of his deliberate choices.***OPPONENT PREVIOUS ARGUMENT***"
